04037nam a22005655i 9780774824309DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20122012xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748243097 a10.59962/97807748243092doi  a(DE-B1597)661631  a(OCoLC)1037937941  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV5620.M35 ǂb S65 2012eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a362.292095181 aSmith, Norman, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIntoxicating Manchuria :bAlcohol, Opium, and Culture in China's Northeast /cNorman Smith. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b41 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Chinese Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAlcohol and Opium in China -- tManchurian Context -- tEvaluating Alcohol -- tSelling Alcohol, Selling Modernity -- tWriting Intoxicant Consumption -- tThe Hostess Scare -- tReasoning Addiction, Taking the Cures -- tThe Opium Monopoly’s “Interesting Discussion” -- tConclusion -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tContemporary Chinese Studies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn China, both opium and alcohol were used for centuries in the pursuit of health and leisure while simultaneously linked to personal and social decline. The impact of these substances is undeniable, and the role they have played in Chinese social, cultural, and economic history is extremely complex. In Intoxicating Manchuria, Norman Smith reveals how warlord rule, Japanese occupation, and political conflict affected local intoxicant industries. These industries flourished throughout the early twentieth century, even as a vigorous anti-intoxicant movement raged. Through the lens of popular Chinese media depictions of alcohol and opium, Smith analyzes how intoxicants and addiction were understood in this society, the role the Japanese occupation of Manchuria played in their portrayal, and the efforts made to reduce opium and alcohol consumption. This is the first English-language book-length study to focus on alcohol use in modern China and the first dealing with intoxicant restrictions in the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDrinking of alcoholic beverages -- China -- Manchuria -- History -- 20th century. 0aOpium abuse -- China -- Manchuria -- History -- 20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482430940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774824309423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774824309/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles